---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
import { withBase } from '../lib/data';
---
<Layout title="Methodology" canonicalPath="/methodology/">
  <header class="page-head narrow"><p class="eyebrow">Methodology</p><h1>Comparable only when the protocol says so.</h1><p class="lede">BioBench Atlas records provenance and evaluation conditions before it records scores. This prevents superficially similar numbers from becoming a misleading leaderboard.</p></header>
  <article class="narrow section prose">
    <h2>v1 inclusion boundary</h2><p>Production exports accept two source classes: benchmark-creator papers or formal technical reports, and official model-provider system cards, release pages, or research pages. Ordinary blogs, secondary leaderboards, and unverified reproductions are excluded. The schema reserves <code>independent_reproduction</code> for a future policy revision.</p>
    <h2>Four entities, four meanings</h2><ol><li><strong>Benchmark</strong> defines the scientific task, access, counts, taxonomy, and runnable status.</li><li><strong>Work</strong> identifies the paper, system card, report, or official page making a claim.</li><li><strong>EvaluationRun</strong> captures one coherent scope and protocol within a work.</li><li><strong>Model</strong> preserves the exact reported model identity without fuzzy merging.</li></ol>
    <div class="callout info"><strong>Run-splitting rule:</strong> a different subset, prompt, tool, budget, grader, repeat count, or reasoning mode is a different run—even if the work and model are the same.</div>
    <h2>Scope is explicit</h2><p><code>full</code> is accepted only when the realized <code>n</code> matches the benchmark version total. <code>subset</code> requires a subset ID, filter, and realized count. <code>track</code> refers to a formal benchmark track. When the source does not let us determine these, scope is <code>unknown</code>; we do not infer full coverage.</p>
    <h2>Missing means missing</h2><p>Unreported values use <code>null</code> plus <code>reporting_status: not_reported</code>. Zero is never used as a missing-value code. The LifeSciBench binding example demonstrates the difference: binding is explicitly in scope, but no standalone count is reported.</p>
    <h2>Metrics and comparability</h2><p>Metrics retain their source label, unit, direction, range, aggregation, threshold, and tolerance. Result rows only reference a metric declared by their run. Charts compare models only inside an explicit <code>comparability_group</code>, which must agree on benchmark version, scope, metric, and key protocol settings.</p>
    <div class="callout"><strong>No universal life-science score.</strong> We do not normalize across benchmarks or publish a cross-benchmark “best model” ranking.</div>
    <h2>Evidence</h2><p>Each critical field points to an official work plus a locator—page, section, figure, or table—and lists the JSON paths it supports. Remote papers and webpages are linked rather than mirrored unless redistribution permission is explicit.</p>
    <h2>Release and reproducibility</h2><p>Verified YAML is validated, normalized once, and emitted as website data, JSON, CSV, and schemas. Monthly release snapshots are maintainer-triggered and immutable. Weekly link checks open issues but never mutate facts.</p>
    <p class="button-row"><a class="button" href={withBase('/contribute/')}>Contribution protocol</a><a class="button secondary" href={withBase('/data/registry.json')}>Inspect normalized JSON</a></p>
  </article>
</Layout>
